ons to this collection show, housing allowances are not without problems of their own, especially in relation to housing consumption and work incentives. This book examines income-related housing allowance schemes in advanced welfare states as well as in transition economies of central and eastern Europe. Drawing on experiences in ten countries, including Britain, Sweden, Germany, Australia and the USA, it presents new evidence on the origins and design of housing allowances; their role within housing and social security policy; their impact on affordability; and current policy debates and recent reforms. Unique in it's depth of coverage, Housing Allowances in Comparative Perspective is essential reading for researchers, students and lecturers in social policy, housing and urban studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aHousing subsidieszGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aElsinga, Marja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulse, Kath, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKofner, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLux, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Sandra J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPriemus, Hugo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSatsangi, Madhu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteele, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSunega, Petr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThorns, David C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab